## Deprecated vs Removed

The C++ standard uses two distinct statuses:

- **Deprecated** — the feature is officially considered obsolete; the compiler must issue a warning, but the code still compiles. The expectation is removal in a future standard.
- **Removed** — the feature is no longer part of the standard; code using it won't compile.

C++20 made important steps in both categories.

---

## Deprecated in C++20

### volatile — first wave of deprecation (P1764)

`volatile` is one of the most misunderstood specifiers in C++. In C++20, three specific patterns became deprecated:

1. **Compound assignments** (`+=`, `-=`, `++`, `--`, etc.) on `volatile` variables:
   ```cpp
   volatile int v = 0;
   v += 1;  // C++20: deprecated, use v = v + 1
   ++v;     // C++20: deprecated
   ```
   Reason: these operations read, modify, and write — none of which is guaranteed to be atomic. This creates a false sense of safety.

2. **`volatile` as a function parameter type**:
   ```cpp
   void f(volatile int x);  // C++20: deprecated
   ```

3. **`volatile` as a return type**:
   ```cpp
   volatile int get();  // C++20: deprecated
   ```

`volatile` remains valid and **not deprecated** for memory-mapped I/O (hardware registers), where the specifier means "every memory access actually matters, don't optimize it away".

The modern replacement for shared state between threads is `std::atomic<T>`.

---

### std::iterator as a base class

A very old pattern was inheriting from `std::iterator<Category, T, ...>` to get all the necessary typedefs in one shot:

```cpp
// C++17 and earlier — deprecated in C++17, removed in C++20
struct MyIter : std::iterator<std::forward_iterator_tag, int> {
    // iterator_category, value_type, etc. inherited automatically
};
```

The problem: such a base class is completely opaque when reading the code — it's not obvious which types are being provided. The modern style is to declare them explicitly as member typedefs:

```cpp
struct MyIter {
    using iterator_category = std::forward_iterator_tag;
    using value_type        = int;
    using difference_type   = std::ptrdiff_t;
    using pointer           = int*;
    using reference         = int&;
    // ... implementation
};
```

This is clear, introduces no base-class dependency, and is exactly how iterators are implemented in all modern libraries.

---

### std::allocator\<T\>::construct and destroy

`std::allocator_traits` appeared in C++11 as the single point of access to allocator functions, providing default implementations. Calling `alloc.construct(p, args...)` and `alloc.destroy(p)` directly became redundant and was deprecated:

```cpp
// Deprecated in C++17, targeted for removal
std::allocator<int> a;
int* p = a.allocate(1);
a.construct(p, 42);  // deprecated
a.destroy(p);        // deprecated

// Modern replacement — via allocator_traits
std::allocator_traits<std::allocator<int>>::construct(a, p, 42);
std::allocator_traits<std::allocator<int>>::destroy(a, p);
```

`allocator_traits` works with any custom allocator, providing sensible defaults when methods are absent.

---

### std::result_of

`std::result_of<F(Args...)>` computed the return type of calling `F` with `Args...`. Deprecated in C++17, removed in C++20.

Replacement: `std::invoke_result_t<F, Args...>`, which is cleaner syntactically (arguments are separate, not wrapped in a pseudo-function-signature) and works correctly with all callable types:

```cpp
// Was (C++14/17)
using T = std::result_of<decltype(f)(int, double)>::type;

// Now (C++17+, preferred)
using T = std::invoke_result_t<decltype(f), int, double>;
```

---

### std::is_pod

`std::is_pod<T>` returned `true` for "Plain Old Data" types — the intersection of trivial and standard-layout. The POD concept turned out to be too coarse and was deprecated in C++20.

Replacement — use more precise predicates explicitly:

```cpp
// Was
std::is_pod_v<T>  // deprecated

// Now — only what you actually need
std::is_trivial_v<T>            // trivial constructor/destructor/copy
std::is_standard_layout_v<T>   // compatible with C structs
std::is_trivially_copyable_v<T>  // safe to memcpy
```

This is more precise: depending on the task, you need one specific predicate, not their intersection.

---

## Removed in C++20

### std::random_shuffle

Deprecated in C++14, removed in C++17 (in practice, in C++20 for some implementations). Reason: it used `std::rand()` internally, giving weak and unpredictable shuffling.

Replacement: `std::shuffle` with an explicit random number generator:

```cpp
// Removed
std::random_shuffle(v.begin(), v.end());  // won't compile in C++20

// Replacement
std::mt19937 rng(std::random_device{}());
std::shuffle(v.begin(), v.end(), rng);
```

### std::binary_function and std::unary_function

Ancient base classes for function objects (C++98), providing `argument_type`, `result_type`, etc. Deprecated in C++11 with the arrival of `std::function` and lambdas, removed in C++17.

```cpp
// Removed
struct Add : std::binary_function<int, int, int> {
    int operator()(int a, int b) const { return a + b; }
};

// Replacement — just a lambda or a plain struct with operator()
auto add = [](int a, int b) { return a + b; };
```

---

## Migration Reference Table

| What | Status in C++20 | Replacement |
|------|----------------|-------------|
| `volatile` compound assign | deprecated | `v = v + 1` or `std::atomic` |
| `volatile` param/return | deprecated | remove `volatile` |
| `std::iterator` base | deprecated (since C++17) | explicit member typedefs |
| `allocator::construct/destroy` | deprecated | `allocator_traits` |
| `std::result_of` | removed (dep. C++17) | `std::invoke_result_t` |
| `std::is_pod` | deprecated | `is_trivial` + `is_standard_layout` |
| `std::random_shuffle` | removed (dep. C++14) | `std::shuffle` + rng |
| `std::binary_function` | removed (dep. C++11) | lambda or plain struct |
| `std::unary_function` | removed (dep. C++11) | lambda or plain struct |

